WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
Mr. Kanhai Chatterjee, he has been one of the senior committee members for a long long time

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:18.000
and has actually been involved in Welsh Puja Committee for over 30 years, probably.

00:00:18.000 --> 00:00:27.000
So, Kanhai, can you say how and when you got involved in Durga Puja and festival?

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:38.000
When I first came to Port Coll after I got married in 1975, obvious reasons that we are looking for somewhere

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:46.000
where the puja is going to take place and that's how we got involved in 1975.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:56.000
So, you were actually involved in the first year or two of puja starting because Durga Puja started in 1974, I think, in somebody's...

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:59.000
After one year we started.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:00.000
Okay.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Okay, Kanhai, who were the people who were there with you at that time? Can you remember?

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
I think I will remember.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:12.000
No, you say it.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:17.000
So far I remember the people involved at that time were

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:28.000
Rama Panchavudri, Tapas Basu, Gopas Santosh Gauray, Sikha Araghosh and Rupen Majumdar.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:36.000
And are you still in contact with some of these people?

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Still in contact with all those people.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:45.000
And I think was Kamal Ghatak there as well? Kamal Ghatak and...

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
There was some other people as well, isn't it? Kamal Ghatak and...

00:01:53.000 --> 00:02:03.000
Kamal Ghatak and Shambhu Das. Shambhu Das were the first... they are the first person who were investigated and...

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Okay, tell me, tell me.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:18.000
Kamal Ghatak and Shambhu Das, I think they are the first people who were very encouraged to start the Durga Puja at the parade.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:28.000
So they are the one probably, you think, brought the puja from somebody's house to the Sarvajananda Puja in the parade?

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:32.000
I can confirm that.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:33.000
Yes, it is.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:34.000
It was?

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:41.000
Yes, because the puja used to be held in a very small way in, I think, in Kamal Ghatak's house.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:49.000
And then Kamal Ghatak brought it with the help of Shambhu Das to... in parade in Kharadev.

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:54.000
Right. Thank you very much, Anamika, for filling that up because...

00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:04.000
Anamika Chatterjee, she's also been involved same time as Kanhai Chatterjee, his good wife, and she's still involved in our puja.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Can you, Kanhai, can you share some of your memories of the first puja when you attended it?

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:16.000
What sort of puja it was like back in 1975?

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:30.000
When we attended the puja, I remember particularly the ladies were involved much in actually making the puja offerings and taking somebody's house,

00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:40.000
like in Port Collie in our house and Auroghosa's house and Roma Pachaudhuri house in Kharadev.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:43.000
Can I join in?

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:45.000
Yeah, yeah, can we join in? That's fine, yeah.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:52.000
Yes, I remember it because it was my first puja after coming from Kolkata, India.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:04.000
And I was a newly bride, so it was very exciting for me to go and see a Durga puja happening in Wales, you know.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:14.000
So when I went there, there were lots of activities were going on, but nowadays all the cooking and everything gets done in the hall.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:26.000
Those days we were not that lucky to have all the accommodation, so we only had a hall to have the puja, all the offerings, everything,

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:35.000
but actual the feeding part, what the logs of people come and have food with us, we didn't have that space.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:42.000
So I remember we used to come back to Puthkol to make Rasagulla and Shikhar Gosha's house.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:57.000
And Dr. Tapash Gosha, his wife, Sampa Bosh, Gopa, myself, Roma Pachaudhuri, and we all used to go to Roma Pachaudhuri's house to make Khichuri and Labra.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:02.000
So we just divided all the cooking into different houses, you know.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:09.000
So we used to travel in the morning, come back at lunch time, cook all the food for the people who is going to attend puja,

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:15.000
and go back to Kharif. So it was much more harder work that time.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:26.000
That's really fascinating, Anamika. Do you think that also, other than the community spirit, there was also a financial reason for this?

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:34.000
That it was not very, the organization was not very well offered at that time, or limited financial resources?

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:42.000
I think so, because puja wasn't held, it was only the beginning of puja in Kharif.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:53.000
So it wasn't held at a much bigger scale as it is happening now. So we had less resources, financial resources.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:01.000
I remember people used to come to our house, get Khanai, they used to go around people's houses to collect puja.

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:09.000
I wanted to say, because the next question is number five, what made the challenges in the house?

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:20.000
So we'll come to the challenges. So just to complete what Anamika was saying, you went around the houses to actually involve.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:21.000
Yes, I remember myself.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:27.000
So let's come to that, that what were the challenges you both feel was at that time in the puja?

00:06:27.000 --> 00:06:38.000
I remember I myself with Tapas Basu used to go in different, in Kharif, in Swansi, in other places, nearby places,

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:46.000
to collect chada, what we call their contribution for the puja.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:53.000
And it was very difficult, because at that time we are not sure how many Indian people,

00:06:53.000 --> 00:07:00.000
particularly Bengali people, is around in Swansi areas or even in Brijan and Port Co.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
And that was a major challenge we found out at that time.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:07.000
You want to add something?

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:17.000
It was a challenge because in relation to puja what's happening now is there is more, much more publicity,

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:24.000
advertisement, which attracting people to come to their nearest place to have Durga Puja,

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:30.000
because this is very special time for the Bengali all over India.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.000
It's puja is held in different names. We call it Durga Puja.

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:37.000
In some parts of India is called something different, you know.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:41.000
So it's very important to all Indians.

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:47.000
But that time we didn't have the measurement of publicity that much.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:52.000
So it was just word of mouth.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:02.000
So, Anamika, you were saying that it was a lot of challenge and Kanaida saying lot of challenges as well.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:08.000
How did you actually manage to identify people whose house to go to and knock for chada those days?

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
That's by word of mouth.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:17.000
Somebody I was asking where some Indian, particularly Bengali people are living.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:26.000
And of course the people who are around in this area, they were feeding us with all those addresses and the name of the people.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:37.000
Yes, it is like as an association, Indian association in Kharif, we already knew quite a few people.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:42.000
Doctors over the place, Bridgen, Swansea, Merthyr, Kharif.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:52.000
So it was a challenge to collect donations and to run puja for six days.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:09:01.000
And of course lot of people used to ring in our to find out if there any puja going on in the Indian area.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:04.000
And that's also word of mouth.

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:09.000
And it started spreading all over Wales and outside.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:19.000
Just I wanted to concentrate a little bit about this time to connect chada and get the financial resources.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:26.000
Because it's much more easier, I understand now, because everything is collected in the premises on four or five days.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:29.000
And people come there. We don't go people's houses.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:38.000
And when you did that, it was before the days of Internet, before the days of mobile phone, only the house sort of landline phones.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:47.000
Can you both of you, can you give some experiences, bad and good experiences about going in people's house and collecting chada?

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:51.000
Kaneda, can you remember any bad or good experiences?

00:09:51.000 --> 00:10:03.000
I would say it was rather interesting experience because of the reason Bengali people wanted to know if there any Duga puja around the area.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:10.000
And they were very pleased to contribute whatever they can.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:13.000
And they did it very gladly.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:22.000
They accepted it. And obviously from them, other people used to knew what puja is going on.

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:27.000
And that's how it started growing, the whole thing in there.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:30.000
Anamika, you want to add something on that?

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:38.000
Well, I wasn't, I remember Kanai used to go out and collect donation for puja.

00:10:38.000 --> 00:11:00.000
Obviously I didn't have first hand experience, but what I used to have heard that sometimes it was a bit difficult sometimes to go and ask for donations and wait for their perceptions of how they want to do it.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:08.000
So I didn't have any first hand experience, so I'm sorry I can't really add anything extra to it.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:18.000
So the chanda collection at that time, probably each chanda you got took probably half an hour, 45 minutes or an hour because of the travel.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:26.000
Then you have to discuss those with the people you are collecting the chanda and all that and give them the information about the puja.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:30.000
Which now it takes less than a couple of minutes.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:42.000
At that time of course it was time taking because you need some transport, not necessarily you always have the transport, you may have to go by bus to somebody's house.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:54.000
And that's how it happened, but at the end of the day we succeeded in collecting at least some contributions from the people involved.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:08.000
Can you remember anything which actually one thing or two things or three things which sticks out in your mind going back 40 years?

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:20.000
The most important thing which sticks out in my mind is first of all is collecting chanda which is the contribution of people.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:30.000
And secondly to particularly to prepare offerings for the goddess Durga.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:42.000
For example the ladies were involved in cooking khichdi, labra and making rasagullas in somebody's house.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:52.000
And these sort of things were really very exciting at that particular moment and of course encouraged everybody to get involved.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:59.000
And a lot of volunteers then started coming in and saying can I do something, can I do this and that's how it happened.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:02.000
Do you want to add something?

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:14.000
For me it was something obviously I was so new came to this country in 1975 April and Durga puja in October.

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:27.000
So within five months I couldn't believe that something like this a big gathering, it's not just religious is it, it's a social gathering as well.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:43.000
So to go there from the morning meet so many people and do all the work what was necessary to complete the puja it was an overwhelming experience.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:56.000
With friends, the people I didn't know, I met so many people apart from the religious side of it I wasn't that much involved in doing like what I do now.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:05.000
But it's just a massive experience and it's a very joyful experience.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:18.000
So do you think that puja, Durga puja and the festival going back in Wales for 40 years has actually helped in creating your circle and social contact and socialâ€¦

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:39.000
Of course it is because this is the only opportunity once a year to go to Durga puja and meet lots of friends, make new friends and by word of mouth the horizon, the boundaries started expanding.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:57.000
A lot of other people came to know the people 70, 80 miles away from Bristol used to come to the puja and of course it was the greatest opportunity to meet everybody, to exchange views, exchange what you call the gifts.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:18.000
Know how their health or their wealth and how their children doing and all sorts of exchange of ideas this took place and that is the greatest opportunity almost once a year for everybody to get together.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:27.000
And that's how the whole thing started growing in Wales, in particular in our Kadi puja.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:41.000
And if I remember on 40 years ago and comparing in two days of course the number of people at that particular time was not that many.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:53.000
What we can see now we are more than about two and a half, three thousand people coming in over five days in recent years.

00:15:53.000 --> 00:16:21.000
Yes, it is just meeting everybody, people we don't meet regularly, we meet once a year there and especially what fascinates me now I'm talking about that like all the youngsters are coming here to work and I go round and talk with them and

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:37.000
it's a greatest pleasure for them, so young, coming here and attending Durga Puja, meeting people socially. It's a great pleasure.

00:16:37.000 --> 00:17:01.000
And do you think that in that interaction there is also an ongoing opportunity of transfer of experience about you or your life in this country or the society of this country to the younger people who have just come, they may ask you a few questions about the society, about other things which you may be able to help them with.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:29.000
Yeah, definitely. Lots of youngsters we have met, they have asked me different questions, how was puja used to be or what did you do then, what should you do, you know, so as an experienced person living in this country over 40 years, I think that's a lot of help to youngsters to settle them down well. So yes, it is.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:58.000
I remember I used to work in a steel company and a lot of young people from India, from Tata Steel, an Indian steel company, they used to visit to put talbot work and of course some of them used to live in Port Coal and some used to live in Port Talbot and they of course very much interested in being a Bengali person to find out if there are any Durga Puja going on and if there are any other things that are going on.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:28.000
And that's how youngsters got involved and once one group of people from India, they knew that Durga Puja is going on but then from the water mouth, other people living in this area around 80 miles or 90 miles they knew that Durga Puja is going on in the Cardiff area and obviously they used to come there and enjoy themselves.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:52.000
And that's how the whole thing started growing up and over the years, since 40 years ago and today we can see that a lot of people got benefited by knowing that Puja is still going on and is still going well in that area.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:19:14.000
I understand Kanahida Anonymous as well that in the last 15 years or so you have actually been first helping and then being the main priest of Durga Puja. Can you tell us your experience about that and how you got involved like that?

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:36.000
I remember in 2000, year 2000, I had a phone call from Dr. Acharje. I called him Dada. He asked me over the telephone that whether I am interested in doing the Puja, Durga Puja.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:56.000
I was really very scared at that time because Durga Puja is not an easy thing to do. It needs a lot of involvement and not only that, there was also what we call religious fear behind me.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:19.000
Whether I am going to succeed, what is going to happen to me if I am not doing that thing particularly well. Then I completely rejected the idea. Dr. Acharje came back to me again and asked me that Kanahida, there is nobody here who can perform the Puja.

00:20:19.000 --> 00:20:39.000
I was thinking who should be suitable for this opportunity. Then I told him that I have to ask my family in India whether I can actually perform the Puja ceremony.

00:20:39.000 --> 00:20:57.000
I had a very good, positive answer back from home. I said to Acharje that of course, as you asked me that there is nobody available, therefore put my name in. I will try my best.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:09.000
This way in year 2000, Dr. Acharje said that you don't have to worry about anything. I am going to teach you everything from the very beginning.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:29.000
Therefore what happened was that about 3-4 months before the Durga Puja started, I started going to Dr. Acharje's house. He showed me every nitty-gritty of the everyday things I was involved in.

00:21:29.000 --> 00:21:51.000
That's how it started. Of course, the first year it was so difficult for me. I was a bit nervous. Once I started doing the first day of what we call Shastri, then Saptami, Ostami, they all started becoming more and more easier for me.

00:21:51.000 --> 00:22:07.000
I grew in confidence. This way, it started in year 2000. I enjoyed it very much to be honest. From that experience, I got hooked into this whole process.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:13.000
That's a good way of finishing that you got actually hooked into it.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:23.000
Anamika, tell me what Kanhai is doing now, Durga Puja. He is our main priest. He is actually the chief priest. How does it affect you?

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:49.000
Well, as Kanhai is the priest, I became his assistant, you can say. But I had to learn lots of things from Mrs. Acharya. All the religious rituals, which are very, very complicated.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:23:08.000
Eventually, I learned it. We all went to school and learned various things in our life. Very similar way. I learned all the process and why we do this, what needs to be done, how many of these, how many of that.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:31.000
So I became very involved each year. From 2000 year, 2000 till now. It's a huge responsibility. Since Mrs. Acharya passed away, I feel that the whole responsibility that is obviously after Kanhai is on my shoulder.

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:52.000
I need to do everything, all the rituals as I have learned, as best as I could. I am also teaching youngsters how to do it, what to do, why we are doing it, what needs to be done on each day. So it's a big responsibility.

00:23:53.000 --> 00:24:03.000
So it's like what comes to me, listening to both of you, is going like a generational teaching from one generation to another generation.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:18.000
Yes, we learned. Kanhai was Dr. Acharya's student. He was a very obedient student. I never seen anybody going there and learning and trying to understand Sanskrit from our friend Ramadi, Ramachaudhuri.

00:24:18.000 --> 00:24:36.000
And understanding the meaning so that he understands what he is doing. He did it religiously and he is still doing it religiously. And that even makes me feel more responsible to do my part sincerely.

00:24:37.000 --> 00:24:40.000
That's great. What do you say about that?

00:24:40.000 --> 00:25:00.000
Kanhai, can you just say first that how you think the puja has actually grown and evolved in the last 25, 30 or 40 years? How you feel about how the puja has grown and the festival has grown?

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:21.000
Obviously, the Durga Puja is very much a social as well as religious event. And the people who are particularly Bengali, they are interested to find out that is there any puja going on in the Cardiff area?

00:25:21.000 --> 00:25:47.000
Yes, there is a puja going on in the Cardiff area. And from the one of Maud and to their friends, it started. And a lot of people from over the years, like young doctors, young steelworkers, engineers started in about 70, 80 miles area around Cardiff.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:26:03.000
And they were all interested to come into the puja. And in the last 20 years, last 15 years, which I have been involved as a priest, I have noticed there was almost a steady growth of people.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:21.000
And over 15 years, I am not sure whether that is due to what they like my puja, I mean my performance during the puja ceremony.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:40.000
And in this way, a lot of people got involved over the years and still growing. And now we've got a new generation of youngsters who became members of the Wales Puja Committee.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:27:02.000
And they have shown very much interest in doing whatever is required to do. And in this way, I find out the festival, particularly the number of people started growing and the frontiers, the horizon started expanding over the years.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:16.000
And of course, I am very much pleased and get a lot of pleasure out of it, knowing that people are still interested and they contribute whatever they can over the years.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:17.000
Can I come into it?

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:19.000
Yes, yes, Anamika, you come into it.

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:35.000
And you said how the puja evolved since last 25, 30 years. The main theme of the puja is still very similar. Like it's a very family oriented, very friendly way.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:51.000
Like 40 years ago, I have seen it. It just grown in numbers. And it's still very friendly. We welcome everybody. But now I think we've got high tech people here.

00:27:51.000 --> 00:28:15.000
The publicity of Karif Durga Puja is huge. Internet, mobile, telephone calls, letters. These are so many medias that we publicize puja. So puja has evolved around since 1975.

00:28:15.000 --> 00:28:33.000
And it's much larger scale. And all these committee people, they have taken their responsibilities very, very well. 1975, I didn't know that much, 1970 or what used to go on.

00:28:33.000 --> 00:28:42.000
But what I used to see, there are a few people, they always did the work. And I don't know whether there was a committee. I'm sure there was, but I'm not sure.

00:28:42.000 --> 00:29:00.000
But because of high tech, different social media, people's time contributions, everything means a lot more. And puja has grown into much bigger scale than I used to know it.

00:29:00.000 --> 00:29:20.000
1975 till 1980s. Nowadays, wow, people travel even from Swindon, North Wales. Just think about it. How much sincere people are to attend this religious and social festival.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:45.000
And of course, last year, the influence of the high tech, we can see that they are trying to interchange what is going on in Calcutta and what is going on in Karif in particular time.

00:29:45.000 --> 00:30:00.000
They are trying to show the whole puja ceremony, all the rituals, the people involved. And it is only possible because of the growth of what we call the high tech technology.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:20.000
And I remember that particularly when I saw on television that they are showing some excerpts from the Durga Puja in Karif and in Calcutta.

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:41.000
Do you think that coming to another angle that Polyonomica can fully go on first, do you think there is also an angle has changed in terms of cultural activity or programs or functions? Or you think this is the same sort of way used to be in 30, 40 years ago?

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:59.000
Cultural function is going, involvement of people in cultural function is happening in much more larger scales. It also happened because I remember my two little girls, they joined into doing various things, various programs.

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:13.000
But because Karif Indian community was in a much smaller community, but because of the National Health Service, the community has grown into a much bigger one.

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:30.000
And we have more people, all these youngsters coming with so much extracurricular activities and they are teaching their youngsters. So it is happening in a much bigger, larger scale.

00:31:30.000 --> 00:31:42.000
And we didn't have that much of opportunity. There was, I remember, only one lady who is to teach dancing. Ramadi is only the one person who is to teach singing.

00:31:42.000 --> 00:32:08.000
And I remember I even participated, I sang in functions, my children dance and my friends children they dance. But now we have many, many ladies with so many other specialities that they are teaching children, they are taking, they are participating themselves. So yes, it is happening in a much bigger scale.

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:24.000
Can I just ask you last but one question? What do you think is holding the group together? What do you think is the main cement in holding the group together?

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:44.000
I think it is an excellent opportunity for everybody to involve, particularly in puja. As I said, it is once a year, greatest festival in the Hindu calendar.

00:32:44.000 --> 00:33:05.000
